		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/01/business/01bits-it/01bits-it-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/01/business/01bits-it/01bits-it-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/01/business/01bits-it/01bits-it-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002974563" width="592" height="394" alt="In a report issued Monday, Gartner said that global IT spending would be $3.7 trillion in 2014, an increase that&#039;s considerably less than what it had projected for the year previously."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="394"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">In a report issued Monday, Gartner said that global IT spending would be $3.7 trillion in 2014, an increase that's considerably less than what it had projected for the year previously.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Gretchen Ertl for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/01/the-incredible-shrinking-tech-spending-projections/" data-title="The Incredible Shrinking Tech Spending Projections" data-description="It&#039;s something of a ritual: On Monday, an analyst firm lowered its projection for information technology spending. Gartner&#039;s projection change isn&#039;t about economic weakness, however, but the tech we&#039;re using, and how we use it.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Summer is flying by â Gartner has already trimmed its annual projections for worldwide information technology spending. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Why this keeps happening, however, is a story of something very particular: In the current tech transition, analysts are scrambling to figure out how money and technology need now work together.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âFrankly, itâs gotten extremely difficult,â said John-David Lovelock, research vice president at Gartner. âThe things we looked at in 2009 or 2010 arenât the things weâre seeing now. â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a <a href="//www.gartner.com/newsroom/id/2783517 ">report</a> issued Monday, the analysis firm said that global IT spending would be $3.7 trillion in 2014, a 2.1 percent increase from last year. This time a year ago, Gartner <a href="//www.gartner.com/newsroom/id/2537815">thought</a> that 2014 would see a 4.1 percent increase. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How fast things are changing could be seen in one surprising note deep inside the report. Gartner said average revenue per user for voice telecommunications (what our ancestors knew as âphone callsâ) would fall 10 percent a year through 2018. A year ago, Gartner said only that the effect of people moving away from phone calls to things like free Skype calls or texting was âmixed.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The report also said that IT spending was flat in 2013, at $3.673 trillion. A year ago, it had forecast that spending would be up 2.0 percent. In July 2012, Gartner <a href="//www.gartner.com/newsroom/id/2074815">posited</a> that 2013 would see a 4.4 percent rise. That same report also overestimated the spending for 2012 by a full percentage point.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Pointing out these shortfalls is not meant to be a knock on Gartner. In May, IDC <a href="//www.idc.com/getdoc.jsp?containerId=prUS24865914 ">lowered</a> its forecast of global IT spending growth to 4.1 percent, from 4.6 percent. An IDC representative did not respond to messages about whether it would be further revising its forecast.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nor does it mean that analysts are nonstop optimists: Following the 2008-9 financial crisis, Gartner actually <a href="//www.gartner.com/newsroom/id/1735214 ">underestimated</a> how quickly companies would start spending again as they recovered.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/01/technology/01bits-it2/01bits-it2-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/01/technology/01bits-it2/01bits-it2-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/01/technology/01bits-it2/01bits-it2-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002974564" width="190" height="284" alt="John-David Lovelock, research vice president at Gartner."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="284"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">John-David Lovelock, research vice president at Gartner.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The change that is making his job hard, Mr. Lovelock said, is how quickly we are moving to what he called âthe Third Ageâ of IT.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In his view, the first age, from about 1980 to 2000, was one of âIT craftsmanship â we were building computer systems, moving off paper-based payroll and accounting with massive IT departments.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Next, Mr. Lovelock said, was âIT industrialization. It was all about how we can optimize efficiency.â That began in 2000, and is starting to end. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the so-called Third Age, âweâre moving to a world of digital-based businesses,â the analyst said. âTechnology isnât serving an existing business, itâs dictating what a business is.â That is one reason tech spending still grows overall even as it gets cheaper in so many ways: It is needed in more places.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some of the changes in buying would seem relatively easy to spot, like the move from personal computers to tablets, or from computer servers and software to cloud computing systems. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Below the surface, however, things are more complex. Tablets are generally more expensive than basic PCs, for example, but they permit a vastly larger number of organizational systems and can be used with cloud systems in many ways. There are few new buyers for high-end tablets and smartphones, meaning there is increased competition for less expensive devices.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over years of paying subscriptions, cloud software can seemingly cost as much as a software license, but using a cloud service can make it easier for companies to cut staff or redeploy workers to making new kinds of software. Cloud-based data storage is seeing lots of price cutting, too, and the big players are <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/26/technology/google-microsoft-and-others-delve-deeper-into-cloud-storage-for-businesses.html ">scrambling</a> to add features.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What is striking is that, in a period of reasonably modest but stable business conditions for most of the big developed economies, technology spending seems to require less capital than even people close to the matter assume. How it gets used, from sensors to the biggest data centers, may be an even bigger mystery.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt comes down to a much earlier commoditization than we projected,â Mr. Lovelock said. That will end eventually, he said, perhaps more out of hope than evidence. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt has to stabilize,â he said. âPeople will realize they can only take price cutting so far.â </p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	<p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 07/07/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">B</span><span itemprop="printPage">5</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the headline: Spending Is Now Harder to Predict.</p>    </div>
</footer>
